mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Newbigging","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from Newbigging in Carnwath (Lanarks).","2  English:  see  Newbiggin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Newbiggin","meanings":["English: locative name from one or more of the many places so called, such as Newbiggin by the Sea, Newbiggin in Blanchland, Newbiggin in Newburn, Newbiggin in Norham, and Newbiggin in Shotley (all Northumb), East and West Newbiggin in Bishopton, Newbiggin in Heighington, Newbiggin in Lanchester, and Newbiggin in Middleton in Teesdale (all Durham), Newbiggin (Westm), Newbiggin, Newbiggin in Akrigg, Newbegin in Egton, and Newbiggin in Gristhorpe (all NR Yorks), Newbiggin in Croglin, Newbiggin in Dacre, and Newbiggin Hall in Saint Cuthbert Without (all Cumb), Newbigging in Aldingham and a lost  <i>Newbigging</i> in Singleton (both Lancs). The place-names derive from Middle English  <i>neue</i> ‘new’ +  <i>bigging</i> ‘building’. Some of the post-medieval EBs given here may represent the Scottish surname   Newbigging  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret of Newbigging was born in 1190, in Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland. She had at least 3 sons with William de Somerville of Carnwath."},"et":{"1190–":"1190–Surnud","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1232–1300":"1232–1300","1238–1247":"1238–1247","1242–1296":"1242–1296","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1232":"1232","about 1238":"umbes 1238","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","about 1242":"umbes 1242","1183":"1183","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1190–":"1190–Kuollut","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1232–1300":"1232–1300","1238–1247":"1238–1247","1242–1296":"1242–1296","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1232":"1232","about 1238":"noin 1238","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","about 1242":"noin 1242","1183":"1183","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanark